## TL;DR — Four Things to Know

1. **What:** A $1.7 trillion shadow lending market — built on bank regulation, funded partly by pension and annuity money, and largely invisible to regulators — is hitting its first real stress test. Three shocks are converging simultaneously: an oil-shock-driven rate reversal from the Iran war, AI disruption of the ~25% software sleeve of direct lending portfolios, and a $12.7B BDC liability maturity wall in 2026. The market is gating withdrawals in real time.

2. **Why it matters (calibrated):** This is not 2008. Morgan Stanley's analysis confirms that aggregate non-investment-grade credit as a share of GDP is *lower* than pre-GFC — private credit grew by substituting for public credit, not by creating new leverage. The threat is compositional and structural, not systemic: worse borrowers concentrated in opaque vehicles, with recoveries that are genuinely better than BSL (70–80% per MS) due to the single-lender bilateral restructuring advantage. The real damage is credit supply tightening and alt manager equity multiple compression — both real, both partially cyclical.

3. **The calibrated trade:** Manager dispersion within alt managers is the primary expression, not a sector short. OWL has 39% of FPAUM in private credit evergreen/BDC vehicles. BX has 7%. APO has 3%. "Short alt managers broadly" was wrong. The precise trade is short OWL and software-heavy BDCs, selectively long BX/APO/KKR at COVID trough multiples, long quality BDCs like ARCC at 10%+ yield. The spread between best and worst in the BDC universe (-11% ARCC vs -47% TCPC YTD) is the quantified value of underwriting discipline.

4. **What to watch:** Q1 2026 BDC filings in May are the decisive information event — the first marks capturing all three stresses simultaneously. The single most important number: PIK income share, currently 8%, critical threshold 10%. Two variables MS introduces that we hadn't fully priced: (a) recovery rates — the difference between the manageable scenario and the catastrophic one is whether LME bilateral restructuring holds recoveries at 70% or whether AI disruption destroys SaaS business value so completely that even bilateral negotiation yields sub-40% recovery; and (b) whether banks step into the credit supply gap as deregulation enables them to do.

