## 2. How Did It Get So Big? The Regulatory Origin

The short answer: regulation created it. After 2008, Basel III capital requirements and the Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR) made it expensive for banks to hold leveraged middle-market loans. Capital charges were too high relative to returns. Banks retreated. Private credit funds stepped in.

BIS researchers (Doerr, Gelos & Pursiainen, February 2026) proved this causally using a natural experiment: counties where more LCR-constrained banks operated saw significantly more private credit growth after the rule was introduced. The effect was comparable in magnitude to the capital shock from stress tests. **Private credit is a $1.7 trillion regulatory arbitrage.**

This origin story has a forward implication that is underappreciated. The current administration is rolling back those same rules — LCR interpretive FAQs were rescinded February 10, 2026, and Basel III Endgame has already been significantly softened. Morgan Stanley explicitly argues that bank deregulation provides a "strong incentive for banks to increase loan growth," and that bank lending will emerge as "more than an offset to the slowdown in private credit." The structural driver of private credit's growth is partially reversing, and banks are positioned to refill the gap for healthy borrowers. Every alt-manager equity valuation assumes a 14% AUM CAGR — if the regulatory vacuum that generated the asset class is closing, the right CAGR is probably 5–7%.

The Apollo-Athene flywheel amplified this further: Apollo acquired Athene, using insurance policyholder deposits to fund private credit deals. Almost a third of the $6 trillion in US insurer invested assets is now allocated to private credit sub-asset classes. Retail savers are more exposed to this market than their account statements suggest — though MS estimates actual retail equity money at approximately $200–$250 billion of the $1.3 trillion US private credit market, with the remaining 60%+ held by institutional investors in locked-up or long-duration vehicles.

