## 3. The Macro Frame: Not More Levered Than Pre-GFC

Before building the bear case, an honest framing. Morgan Stanley provides the most important context missing from most private credit coverage:

**Aggregate non-investment-grade corporate lending as a share of GDP is lower than pre-GFC.** The HY and loan markets have barely expanded since COVID. Even after accounting for private credit fund growth, total sub-IG corporate lending relative to GDP sits below the 2006–2007 peak. In the years preceding the GFC, corporate leverage had been rising steadily for several years. Today it has stabilised or declined in most advanced economies.

**Private credit grew primarily by substituting for public credit, not by creating net new leverage.** Since 2022, when public credit markets tightened and new-issue access became difficult for highly-levered issuers, private credit stepped in to refinance a large volume of public debt at par. This is documented precisely in MS Exhibit 11 — the BSL-to-DL takeout flow. Private credit financed over 80% of all LBO deals in 2025. What changed is who intermediates credit, not the aggregate amount of risk in the system.

This matters because the macro argument that "the system is more dangerous than ever" is empirically wrong. The problem is **compositional and structural** — worse borrowers have migrated into opaque, illiquidity-premium-charging vehicles with quarterly redemption promises — not a generalised leverage excess. The distinction has real consequences for how systemic the stress can become.

