## 5. The Three Simultaneous Shocks

### Shock 1 — Iran energy shock and rate reversal

Operation Epic Fury (February 28, 2026) pushed Brent crude from $70 to over $100. The Strait of Hormuz carries 38% of global seaborne crude and 20% of global LNG — its effective closure created the largest supply disruption in modern oil market history. Gasoline prices rose $1/gallon in three to four weeks.

The direct consequence for private credit: CME FedWatch flipped from 94% probability of two rate cuts (a month prior) to 19% probability of a rate *hike*. The 10-year Treasury moved from below 4% to 4.5%. For private credit borrowers paying SOFR + 5–6%, this is a direct cash flow hit with no hedge. A 50bp rate increase adds $500M of annual interest expense to every $100B of floating-rate private credit.

Morgan Stanley adds the timing nuance: the softening in private credit sentiment actually predated the Iran shock. The initial catalyst was the Fed's earlier move toward rate cuts, which mechanically reduced income on floating-rate loans that had benefited from the higher-for-longer environment. Spread compression as public and private credit competed for the same borrowers eroded the illiquidity premium. Iran added an acute second shock on top of an already deteriorating return environment.

### Shock 2 — AI disruption of the software sleeve

Software makes up approximately 26% of BDC collateral, 20% of private credit CLO collateral, and 16% of the BSL universe. Software is the single largest sector in each market.

Morgan Stanley's equity colleagues provide an important calibration: AI will reshape software competition but will not eliminate the sector. There will be losers who fail to keep up with innovation, but also highly successful winners who integrate AI into products. The disruption is likely less imminent than market narrative implies — for full AI disruption to occur, data centre and digital infrastructure must be in place first, which is a multi-year capex build. **Refinancing risk likely emerges before actual revenue disruption for many companies.** This is the key MS insight: the default risk is primarily a maturity wall and capital access problem, not an immediate cash flow collapse.

The credit quality of software borrowers is, however, genuinely worse than other sectors. Per S&P Global Ratings, software companies in the private credit universe carry average leverage of 8.0x versus 6.6x for the broader universe, and interest coverage of 1.4x versus 1.7x overall. Over 50% of BSL software issuers are rated B- or lower. The 2021 vintage is disproportionately represented — software loan gross issuance peaked in 2021 at approximately $80bn and these are the borrowers now entering the critical sub-18-month refinancing window.

Software debt entering the under-18-month refinancing window increases materially from March 2026 through end 2027, per Morgan Stanley Exhibit 17. The default pressure therefore accelerates in 2H26, not immediately.

### Shock 3 — The BDC liability maturity wall

Approximately $12.7B of unsecured BDC debt matures in 2026, up 73% versus 2025. This refinancing cycle hits exactly when underlying assets are being marked down. The mechanism that converts illiquidity into solvency: BDCs must issue expensive new debt to repay maturing bonds precisely when their loan portfolios are producing lower income (rate cuts reduced floating-rate yields before Iran reversed the path) and when their assets face softening marks.

