## 6. The Causal Chain — How Stress Spreads Step by Step

Understanding this sequence is what separates the informed view from the headline view.

**Step 1 — Borrower stress accumulates silently.**
A mid-market SaaS company with $200M of private credit debt sees ARR growth slow as AI reduces pricing power. It can't service full cash interest. The lender — often the sole lender — negotiates a PIK toggle rather than force a hard default. The BDC's loan balance grows from $200M to $210M, but no cash comes in. PIK income share in the portfolio rises.

**Step 2 — BDC marks the loan down.**
The valuation committee, advised by an independent third-party appraiser, marks the loan from $200M to $170M. NAV per share drops. Publicly traded BDC stock falls. Non-traded BDC investors read the quarterly report and submit redemption requests.

**Step 3 — Redemption requests hit the gate.**
The fund receives withdrawal requests for 20–40% of assets in a quarter (Blue Owl OTIC: 40.7%). It honors only 5% under its contractual gate. Investors who wanted out are stuck. News of the gate spreads — and, critically, other investors submit requests not because they believe the portfolio is bad, but to beat the next gate. The self-fulfilling dynamic begins. Morgan Stanley notes this is sentiment-driven, not fundamentals-driven, as of early 2026: fund performance, default rates, and non-accruals are still stable-to-date.

**Step 4 — BDC sells assets or stops lending.**
To fund any redemptions, the BDC either sells loans in the secondary market (at 85–99 cents, almost no market; Blue Owl sold $1.4B at 99.7 cents in February) or simply stops making new loans. For healthy borrowers, this is manageable. For borrowers approaching maturity who need refinancing, it is potentially fatal.

**Step 5 — Bank credit lines tighten.**
BDCs borrow from banks against their portfolios (back leverage). Bank credit lines are tied to portfolio marks via borrowing-base tests — if values fall, available credit shrinks. JPMorgan preemptively marked down software loans in March 2026, directly compressing BDC borrowing capacity. However, the look-through math matters here: the bank's effective LTV on a typical structure is approximately 30% (see Section 9), meaning the bank does not feel credit loss pressure until borrower enterprise values fall more than 70%.

**Step 6 — Middle-market credit supply tightens temporarily.**
The real economic damage is not bank failure — it is private credit funds reducing loan commitments, tightening terms, and not renewing facilities for the weakest borrowers. Morgan Stanley's mitigant: bank deregulation enables banks to step into this gap for creditworthy borrowers. The companies that lose access are the ones that were already too risky for banks — and arguably should have defaulted earlier.

**Step 7 — Public markets partially reprice.**
Forced selling by BDCs hits the BSL secondary market (BDCs hold $143B of leveraged loans — more than dedicated loan funds at $120B). This transmits credit stress into public markets, widening spreads. Historically, 100bp of credit spread widening corresponds to approximately 8–10% of equity multiple compression on the S&P 500. The transmission is real but attenuated — the Harvard/NBER stress test shows that as long as BDCs can sell loans (even at small discounts), the bank system absorbs the shock without failures.

**The binary from Chernenko & Scharfstein (Harvard/NBER):**
> If BDCs can sell loans: zero funds default on bank credit facilities in a GFC-equivalent scenario.
> If BDCs cannot sell loans (contractual restrictions or no buyer): 20–35% of funds enter technical default on bank credit lines.
> With bank forbearance: almost all funds cure within the stress test period. Banks suffer no losses.

The entire systemic risk question reduces to one binary: loan sellability. And the most important mitigant for sellability — which the literature agrees on — is that the bilateral single-lender structure makes LMEs (soft restructurings) far more accessible than in the BSL market.

