## 8. The Recovery Rate: The Single Most Important Variable

This section deserves its own treatment because it is where most external commentary — including our earlier analysis — diverges most sharply from Morgan Stanley's bottom-up view.

**The bull case on recovery rates (MS):**
Private credit is not BSL. In BSL, a stressed loan has 50-75 CLO holders, each with a small position. Getting all of them to agree on any restructuring short of formal default is nearly impossible — which is why BSL first-lien loan recovery rates have trended down to approximately $59 (per Moody's, MS Exhibit 18) and US HY bonds to approximately $32 in recent years. Weak covenants and fragmented lender groups mean the only path is formal bankruptcy.

In private credit, the bilateral single-lender structure inverts this. One lender, one borrower, one set of covenants (which are maintenance-based, not incurrence-based). Distressed exchanges involving modest haircuts, incremental coupon, fresh equity from the PE sponsor, and maturity extension are the standard resolution. MS projects 70–80% recovery on this basis.

Sponsor equity cushion confirms this: in tech BSL LBOs over the past seven years, PE sponsors contributed approximately 50% equity on average. Sponsors with $3 billion of equity invested in a $6 billion enterprise do not walk away easily — they negotiate.

**The bear case on recovery rates:**
The recovery rate advantage disappears in one specific scenario: AI disruption so complete that the SaaS business has near-zero residual value as a going concern, and no hard assets to liquidate. For a pure ARR-model company that borrowed at 8× ARR with no EBITDA, if AI competitors eliminate the entire ARR within the loan's life, there is nothing to recover against. This is not hypothetical — it is the thesis for the most vulnerable application-layer SaaS companies, particularly single-function products that perform tasks now available free or near-free from AI systems.

The resolution: the recovery rate question resolves into a question of which software companies are genuinely at extinction risk versus which are mission-critical, deeply embedded, and will adapt. Blackstone focuses on $4.5B average TEV, deeply embedded enterprise software with high switching costs. OWL's tech fund includes a wider range of smaller, less-embedded businesses. ARCC, Sixth Street, and TSLX have lower software exposure. The recovery rate variable is therefore fund-specific, not sector-wide.

**Practical implication for position sizing:**
Do not use a single recovery rate assumption across the sector. The correct approach is to ask, for each specific fund: what is the average TEV of software borrowers, what percentage are ARR-model versus EBITDA-positive, and what is the covenant protection package? That analysis puts Blackstone, Apollo, and quality BDC managers in one bucket (70–80% recovery likely) and the most tech-exposed, covenant-lite, ARR-lending vehicles in another (40–50% recovery plausible).

