## 10. The Three Bear Case Dimensions MS Doesn't Resolve

Despite the calibrating power of the Morgan Stanley analysis, three dimensions of the bear case receive no meaningful treatment in their report and remain the strongest arguments for sustained stress.

### 10.1 The Insurance Transmission Channel

MS discusses insurer exposure briefly but does not stress-test it. JPMorgan Private Bank puts the aggregate closer to a third of the $6 trillion in US insurer invested assets allocated across private credit sub-asset classes. PE-affiliated insurers (Athene/Apollo, Global Atlantic/KKR, F&G/FNF) hold an estimated $1 trillion in assets through those PE relationships.

The critical distinction from banks: insurers carry private credit at **amortised cost**, not fair value. Losses accumulate silently in book values that never move until a capital ratio threshold is breached. When solvency erosion hits PE-affiliated insurers, it constrains annuity issuance, tightens the permanent capital available for new PE investment, and removes a key provider of long-term credit capital from the system. This is a slow-burn, hard-to-detect channel. Unlike banks, which have FDIC monitoring, quarterly stress tests, and publicly visible mark-to-market loan loss provisioning, insurance solvency erosion is an event that regulators and analysts will detect long after it has already occurred.

UBS Chair Colm Kelleher: "You're seeing massive growth in small rating agencies ticking the box for compliance. The insurance industry, especially in the US, is engaging in ratings arbitrage akin to what banks did with subprime loans before the financial crisis."

### 10.2 The Knightian Uncertainty Discount on Unverifiable Marks

The academic literature (Matvos, Piskorski & Seru; Chernenko & Scharfstein; Wharton's Goldstein) converges on a point that MS's practitioner report does not engage: **the problem is not primarily credit losses but the impossibility of verifying whether marks are accurate in real time**.

Private credit funds mark quarterly using internal models and third-party appraisers. There is no secondary market to test the marks. Reporting lags by 90 days. The marks currently reflecting December 2025 conditions do not capture the Iran shock, the Q1 2026 SaaS revenue deceleration, or the full AI disruption repricing in software equity markets.

The consequence, formalised in the NAV discount decomposition above: the market is not pricing just the expected credit loss — it is pricing a premium for the possibility that the marks are wrong and cannot be verified until something forces a cash settlement. This premium closes not when losses resolve but when marks are verified. The only reliable verifiers are: (a) forced loan sales at observable market prices; (b) quarterly filings that show stable ICR and PIK; (c) maturity events where principal is repaid (or not) at cash settlement.

Until May 2026 filings, the market has no way to distinguish between a BDC that has correctly marked its software book and one that is carrying loans at par that will be zero in six months. The unverifiability premium is therefore rational — and it will persist until information forces resolution.

### 10.3 The LCR Reform Structural Headwind

MS mentions deregulation as a bank-expansion tailwind but does not complete the logic for its mirror implication: if banks re-enter middle-market lending, the structural driver of private credit AUM growth partially reverses. The LCR causal identification paper (Doerr et al., BIS) shows the LCR effect on private credit growth was comparable in magnitude to capital shocks. If LCR reform proceeds — and the FAQs have already been rescinded — the addressable market for private credit AUM growth shrinks structurally.

This is the most important argument for why alt manager equity valuations remain impaired even after the current default cycle resolves. The 14% AUM CAGR baked into consensus models is inconsistent with a world in which banks are re-entering the credit market the rules specifically created private credit to fill. The correct long-run CAGR is probably 5–7%.

