## 13. What Makes This Thesis Wrong? Bull Scenarios

**Bull scenario 1 — Hormuz reopens quickly.** Peace negotiations succeed. Brent falls to $75. Fed returns to two-cut path. SOFR drops 50–75bp. ICR rebounds above 2.0×. Software defaults stay below 5%. The 25% NAV discount on OBDC closes to 10%. All alt manager stocks bounce 20–30%. The entire trade depends on the same geopolitical binary: Middle East peace. This concentration of scenario dependency in one event is itself a risk.

**Bull scenario 2 — AI earnings vindicate the boom.** Hyperscaler revenue beats consensus. Enterprise SaaS companies demonstrate AI augmentation (selling AI tools built on their platforms) rather than disruption. Private credit software defaults stay 3–5%. The "25% of portfolios exposed to AI disruption" narrative is reframed as "25% of portfolios exposed to AI upside."

**Bull scenario 3 — May filings are clean.** Q1 2026 BDC filings show ICR stable at 2.0%+ and PIK income below 8%. The 90-day lag means these marks reflect Q1 2026 — the first capturing all three shocks simultaneously. If they hold, the unverifiability premium collapses. Quality BDCs rerate from discount to premium. ARCC, BXSL, TSLX all materially higher.

**Bull scenario 4 — Rotation, not exodus.** KKR private wealth flows $3.9B in Q1 largely from PE and infrastructure. BXPE March flows were a monthly record. BREIT first net inflow since 2022 in February 2026. Money leaving private credit is rotating within alternatives to PE, infrastructure, and secondaries — not abandoning the asset class. BREIT resolved its gate in 15 months. BCRED, well-managed, resolves similarly. For long-horizon institutional investors (CLOs, insurance, pensions), private credit remains the preferred yield enhancement tool.

**Bull scenario 5 — Banks more than offset.** Basel III Endgame rollback, removal of leveraged lending guidelines, and LCR reform give banks capacity and incentive to grow C&I lending (currently $3T, already exceeding private credit in size). For healthy mid-market borrowers, the credit supply does not contract — it transitions to a different intermediary. Only the marginal, over-leveraged, AI-disrupted software company loses access — which MS argues is the correct economic outcome.

