## 14. How the Trade Plays Out — Phase by Phase

**Phase 1: The Sentiment Crisis — Now through May 2026**

Redemption gates dominate headlines. OWL, Apollo, Ares, BlackRock, KKR all gating. Alt manager stocks at 2026 lows. Sector has lost $132B in market cap. Sentiment is negative beyond what fundamentals justify, per MS.

*The trade here:* Quality BDC weakness (ARCC, BXSL) is sentiment-driven — buy. Weak BDC weakness (OBDC, TCPC, OWL equity) is at least partially fundamental — short or avoid. Diversified alt managers (BX, APO, KKR) at COVID trough multiples on fee-related earnings are increasingly attractive on a 12–18 month horizon.

*The decisive event: Q1 2026 BDC filings in May.*

**Phase 2: The Mark-to-Reality Reckoning — May through September 2026**

Q1 filings land. If ICR has deteriorated and PIK has risen above 8%, the bear case strengthens materially. Dividend cuts follow (base dividend coverage already averaging 99%). More non-accruals recognized. Software debt entering sub-18M refinancing window ($40B+ by July 2026, rising to $80B+ by November 2027 per MS Exhibit 17) begins forcing cash settlements or LMEs.

If filings are clean, the unverifiability premium collapses rapidly. Quality BDCs rerate 15–25% higher within weeks.

**Phase 3: The Default and Restructuring Cycle — H2 2026 through 2027**

Morgan Stanley's 8% annual private credit default rate runs from 2H26 through 1H27. Most of these defaults will be distressed exchanges (LMEs), not bankruptcies — hence the 70–80% recovery rate expectation. Distressed funds begin deploying meaningfully. PE sponsors hand over equity in companies unable to refinance. Banks re-enter on their own terms for creditworthy borrowers.

The real economic consequence: approximately 10% of private credit borrowers face materially tighter conditions. The rest refinance through banks or reprice into BSL. Credit supply does not vanish — it shifts.

**Phase 4: The Reset and Private Credit 2.0 — 2027 through 2029**

Direct lending to sub-investment-grade software companies reprices from a premium to a discount. Asset-backed finance overtakes direct lending as the dominant strategy. The industry consolidates around five to eight mega-managers. New vintages (2026–2027 loans) will have tighter covenants, lower leverage, and smaller software exposure — they may be among the strongest vintages of the cycle.

Distressed fund LPs harvest 15–25% IRRs on 2026–2027 vintage positions. Quality BDC investors who bought at 2026 lows collect 10%+ yield while marks recover. The LCR reform-driven structural headwind limits AUM CAGR to 5–7% rather than 14%.

