## 16. Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **ABF (Asset-Backed Finance)** | Private credit loans backed by hard assets (aircraft, data centres, mortgages, auto loans) rather than corporate cash flows. Structurally safer in a downturn because collateral can be sold independently of borrower solvency. |
| **Amortised cost accounting** | Recording assets at their original purchase price adjusted for amortisation, not current market value. Insurance companies use this — allowing them to avoid marking private credit losses to market until capital ratio thresholds are breached. |
| **ARR (Annual Recurring Revenue)** | Total predictable annual subscription revenue. Some private credit lenders underwrote loans based on "X times ARR" rather than EBITDA during 2020–2022. This is aggressive underwriting that works only if the recurring revenue persists. |
| **BDC (Business Development Company)** | A regulated fund structure created by Congress in 1980 to finance small businesses. BDCs can borrow up to 1× their equity (100% leverage cap). Publicly traded BDCs must disclose every loan quarterly. Non-traded BDCs offer periodic redemptions but no live price discovery. |
| **BSL (Broadly Syndicated Loans)** | Large corporate loans originated by banks and sold to many institutional investors (typically 50–75 CLOs per loan). The public equivalent of private credit. Has a functioning secondary market. The coordination failure in distressed situations (50–75 lenders must agree) is what makes recoveries lower than private credit. |
| **Covenant** | A contractual restriction on the borrower. Maintenance covenants require the borrower to maintain certain financial ratios at all times. BSL loans are largely "covenant-lite" (fewer restrictions). Private credit loans typically have stronger maintenance covenants — a key advantage in restructuring. |
| **Distressed exchange (LME)** | A soft restructuring short of formal bankruptcy: modest principal haircut, incremental coupon, equity injection from PE sponsor, maturity extension. Much easier in private credit (one lender) than BSL (50–75 lenders). This is why MS projects 70–80% recovery on PC defaults. |
| **EBITDA** | Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation and Amortisation. The primary measure of a private company's operating cash generation used in credit underwriting. |
| **Financial ouroboros** | A self-referential financial system where participants simultaneously invest in, borrow from, and sell to each other — inflating valuations without external demand validation. Applied to AI sector circular financing (Nvidia/OpenAI/Oracle/AMD reciprocal investment loop). |
| **ICR (Interest Coverage Ratio)** | EBITDA ÷ interest expense. 2.0× = earns twice what it pays in interest. Below 1.0× = technically cannot service debt from operations. Private credit direct lending currently hovering around 2.0× (JPMorgan) with improvement of 25% YoY at BCRED. |
| **Knightian uncertainty** | Risk that cannot be quantified because the underlying probabilities are unknown — as opposed to calculable risk. The unverifiability of private credit marks introduces Knightian uncertainty: not just "what are the losses" but "can we even know what the losses are?" This justifies the NAV discount premium beyond pure credit loss estimates. |
| **LBO (Leveraged Buyout)** | Acquisition of a company using primarily debt (often 5–6× EBITDA). Private equity firms use LBOs heavily. Private credit financed over 80% of all LBO deals in 2025 per PitchBook/LCD. |
| **LCR (Liquidity Coverage Ratio)** | Basel III rule requiring banks to hold enough liquid assets to survive a 30-day stress event. BIS research causally identifies LCR introduction as a comparable driver of private credit growth to capital shocks. LCR reform = structural headwind for private credit AUM. |
| **NAV (Net Asset Value)** | Book value of a fund's assets minus its liabilities, per share. The NAV discount is the gap between this book value and the market price — driven partly by credit loss expectations and partly by an illiquidity/unverifiability premium. |
| **NDFI (Non-Depository Financial Institution)** | Banks' broad category for lending to financial institutions that do not take deposits. Includes lending to BDCs, CLO vehicles, private equity funds, leasing companies, and others. Private credit is a sub-component. Much of the 2024–2025 NDFI growth reflects FDIC reclassification from C&I, not new exposure. |
| **PIK (Payment In Kind)** | When a borrower defers cash interest by adding principal. Currently ~8% of BDC investment income industry-wide. Above 10% historically precedes hard defaults by 1–2 quarters. |
| **Recovery rate** | The cents on the dollar a lender recovers when a borrower defaults. Private credit: ~70–80% (MS estimate) due to strong covenants + single-lender LME flexibility. BSL first liens: declining toward $59 in recent years due to covenant-lite structures and fragmented lenders. SaaS companies: potentially lower due to asset-light nature if business model is disrupted. |
| **SOFR** | Secured Overnight Financing Rate, replacing LIBOR as the benchmark for floating-rate loans. Private credit loans priced at SOFR + 500–600bp. When the Fed raises rates, borrower interest bills rise automatically. |

